{"id":"1812.06276","submitter":"Vasileios Lembessis Dr.","authors":"V. E. Lembessis","title":"Cold atoms interacting with highly twisted laser beams mimic the forces\n  involved in Millikan's experiment","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1555-6611/aaffb8","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper considers the analogy between the force exerted on cold atoms when\nthey interact with a highly twisted tightly focused laser beam and the forces\nexerted on a charged dielectric particle inside a uniform electric field when\nwe perform the Millikan's experiment. In the later case the particle\nexperiences its weight, a force due to the electric field which is arranged in\nthe opposite direction of the weight, and a drag force due to the air\nproportional and opposite to the velocity of the particle. The force due to the\nelectric field is \"quantised\" since the charge of the particle is always an\ninteger multiple of the electron charge. In the case of the cold atoms the\ntotal force is made up by three terms. The second term is quantised since it is\nproportional to the beam helicity which is an integer number. The sign of this\nterm is opposite to the first. The third term is a damping force force\nproportional and opposite to the velocity of the atom. We present numerical\ncalculations with parameters taken from experimental data which show an\nimpressive analogy between the involved forces.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 15 Dec 2018 11:59:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-02-20"}
